      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Why is iron so important during pregnancy?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Iron is essential during pregnancy because blood volume increases by 30-50% to support fetal growth, placental development, and increased red blood cell production. The recommended daily iron intake doubles from 18mg to 27mg during pregnancy. Iron deficiency anemia during pregnancy is associated with preterm birth, low birth weight, postpartum depression, and impaired infant cognitive development. The WHO estimates that 40% of pregnant women worldwide are anemic, with iron deficiency being the primary cause. Without adequate supplementation, maternal iron stores are depleted to supply the fetus, often leaving mothers severely depleted postpartum.' },
