      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do prenatal iron gummies cause constipation?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Iron supplements are a well-known cause of constipation during pregnancy, which is already a common complaint. However, the iron forms used in modern prenatal gummies — ferrous bisglycinate and ferric pyrophosphate — cause significantly less constipation than traditional ferrous sulfate. A 2014 study in the Journal of Perinatal Medicine found that ferrous bisglycinate produced 70% fewer GI side effects than ferrous sulfate at equivalent iron doses. To further reduce constipation risk: take iron with vitamin C to improve absorption (allowing lower effective doses), stay well-hydrated, consume adequate fiber, and consider a magnesium supplement, which has mild laxative properties.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'When should I take prenatal iron gummies?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'For optimal iron absorption, take prenatal iron gummies on an empty stomach or with a vitamin C source — orange juice, strawberries, or bell peppers. Iron absorption is highest when stomach acid is present, so taking it between meals (1 hour before or 2 hours after eating) is ideal. However, if iron causes nausea on an empty stomach — common during pregnancy — taking it with a small meal is acceptable, with a modest reduction in absorption. Avoid taking iron within 2 hours of calcium supplements, dairy products, coffee, tea, or antacids, as these significantly inhibit iron absorption. Bedtime dosing can also work well and may reduce daytime nausea.' },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How do I know if I need iron in my prenatal?',
      acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'All pregnant women need iron — the question is how much. Routine prenatal blood work includes a complete blood count (CBC) and ferritin level, which measure red blood cell status and iron stores respectively. Normal ferritin during pregnancy is 12-150 ng/mL, with levels below 30 ng/mL indicating depleted stores that may progress to anemia. Symptoms of iron deficiency include fatigue beyond normal pregnancy tiredness, pale skin and nail beds, shortness of breath, dizziness, and ice cravings (pica). Women who enter pregnancy with low iron stores, have closely spaced pregnancies, carry multiples, or follow vegetarian/vegan diets are at highest risk and should prioritize iron-containing prenatals.' },
