    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Prenatal Gummies With Iron</h2>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why is iron so important during pregnancy?</summary>
      <p>Blood volume increases by 30-50% during pregnancy, requiring dramatically more iron for red blood cell production and fetal development. The RDA doubles from 18mg to 27mg. Iron deficiency anemia is associated with a 2.5x increased risk of preterm birth, low birth weight, and impaired infant cognitive development. The WHO estimates 40% of pregnant women worldwide are anemic.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Why do most prenatal gummies not contain iron?</summary>
      <p>Iron has a strong metallic taste, reacts with other vitamins in the gummy matrix, and can cause texture problems. These formulation challenges have led approximately 90% of prenatal gummy brands to exclude iron entirely, making iron-containing options rare and valuable.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>What form of iron is best in prenatal gummies?</summary>
      <p>Ferrous bisglycinate is the gentlest form with 2-4x better absorption than ferrous sulfate and 70% fewer GI side effects. Ferric pyrophosphate is a good slow-release alternative. Avoid ferrous sulfate in gummy format due to strong metallic taste and higher GI side effect rates.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How much iron should a prenatal vitamin contain?</summary>
      <p>The pregnancy RDA is 27mg. Many prenatal gummies with iron provide 9-18mg — a meaningful contribution but not the full requirement. Supplement remaining iron through dietary sources: red meat (2.6mg/3oz), fortified cereals (18mg/serving), lentils (3.3mg/half cup). Women with anemia may need 60-120mg under physician supervision.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Can I take an iron gummy separately from my prenatal?</summary>
      <p>Yes — this is the most common approach. Take iron 2 hours apart from your prenatal, as calcium and zinc compete with iron for absorption. Take iron with vitamin C to enhance absorption, and avoid dairy, coffee, and tea which inhibit it.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>Do prenatal iron gummies cause constipation?</summary>
      <p>Modern gentle iron forms (bisglycinate, pyrophosphate) cause significantly less constipation than ferrous sulfate. A 2014 study found bisglycinate produced 70% fewer GI side effects at equivalent doses. Stay hydrated, consume adequate fiber, and consider magnesium supplementation for additional relief.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>When should I take prenatal iron gummies?</summary>
      <p>For optimal absorption, take on an empty stomach or with vitamin C. Avoid taking within 2 hours of calcium, dairy, coffee, tea, or antacids. If iron causes nausea on an empty stomach, taking with a small meal is acceptable with modest absorption reduction. Bedtime dosing can reduce daytime nausea.</p>
    </details>

    <details class="fq">
      <summary>How do I know if I need iron in my prenatal?</summary>
      <p>All pregnant women need iron. Routine blood work measures CBC and ferritin levels — ferritin below 30 ng/mL indicates depleted stores. Symptoms include fatigue, pale skin, shortness of breath, dizziness, and ice cravings. Women with low stores, closely spaced pregnancies, multiples, or vegetarian/vegan diets are at highest risk.</p>
    </details>

